      "outcome": "“On the one hand for a reader who has studied elementary number theory, and\nwho has knowledge of analytic geometry, differential and integral calculus,\ntogether with the elements of complex variable theory, we wish to introduce\nbasic results from the areas of the geometry of numbers, diophantine approximation, prime number theory, and the asymptotic calculation of number\ntheoretic functions. However on the other hand for the student who has already studied analytic number theory, we also present results and principles\nof proof, which until now have barely if at all appeared in text books. For\nexample these include the proof of the irrationality of the Riemann zeta function\nat the number 3, Newman's application of complex variable theory to the\nprime number theorem, and Hecke's prime number theorem for the Gaussian integers.” —copied from the preface of the reading book.\nKnowledge:\nStudents will understand some classical theorems in geometric and analytic number theory.\n1)\tThe Dirichlet approximation theorem and its applications (linear Diophantine equation, Pell equation, irrationality of 𜗓(3)).\n2)\tThe Kronecker approximation theorem and its applications (Uniform Distribution modulo 1,Weyl's criterion).\n3)\tGeometry of numbers and its applications (Minkowski's lattice point theorem, Lagrange's theorem, Minkowski's and Hlawka's theorem).\n4)\tNumber Theoretic functions (Dirichlet divisor problem, Gauss circle problem, Analytic continuation of the zeta- function).\n5)\tThe prime number theorem (prime number theorem, Hecke's prime number theorem for Z[i]).\n6)\tCharacters of groups of residues (Structure of finite abelian groups, Prime number theorem for arithmetic progressions, Estimate of the smallest primitive root, Quadratic reciprocity theorem, Gauss sums).\n7)\tThe Algorithm of Lenstra, Lenstra and Lovasz.\nSkills\nGeneric:\na)\tStudents will be able to understand and write rigorous proofs.\nb)\tStudents will be able to understand and appreciate the close relations among various branches of mathematics.\nc)\tStudents will be able to study higher-level mathematics and physics, and/or to continue their postgraduate studies in science or engineering\nValued/Attitude:\nd)\tStudents will be able to understand and explain the fundamental concepts and theorems of number theory.\ne)\tStudents will appreciate the use of analysis and geometry in proving important theorems.\nf)\tStudents will be able to understand the importance of number theory to different fields in science, such as cryptography.\ng)\tStudents will obtain the mathematical maturity to appreciate abstract concepts in theoretical science.",
